The Vice President of the United States, Kamala Harris, spoke at the COP26 summit in Dubai, United Arab Emirates, emphasizing the urgency of the climate crisis. She highlighted the need for transformative change and exponential impact, stating that nations must lead with courage and treat the climate crisis as an existential threat. Harris mentioned that the United States has invested a trillion dollars over the next 10 years to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, boost climate resilience, and support adaptation. She proudly announced that the United States has joined more than 115 nations in committing to double energy efficiency and triple renewable energy capacity by 2030. Harris also mentioned the United States' investments in clean energy research and development, as well as efforts to increase renewable energy production and innovation. She emphasized the interconnectedness and interdependence of the world in addressing the climate crisis and highlighted collaborations with Caribbean leaders and initiatives to support women in the sustainable economy. Harris announced the launch of a new partnership to help build clean energy supply chains globally and announced $568 million in concessional lending for clean energy manufacturing. She concluded her speech by urging everyone to share the urgency and optimism of young climate leaders and to work together to build a cleaner, healthier, and more prosperous future for generations to come.